1 Q1: Clustering and PCA

1.1 Clustering

1.1.1 Color of wines

Figure 1.1: Value of features for wines of different colors

Figure 1.1 shows that colors can be most distinguished by volatile.acidity and total.sulfur.dioxide since these two features’ differences in median are significantly large. After running K-means++, we can find that volatile.acidity and total.sulfur.dioxide naturally help divide the wines into 2 groups by Figure 1.2.

Figure 1.2: Features by clusters (color)

This can be confirmed by plotting the true color of wines (Figure 1.3), which shows group 1 refers to the whites and group 2 refers to the reds.

Figure 1.3: Features by actual labels (color)

The confusion matrix gives the precision of using K-means++ to differ the reds from the whites.

##        yhat
## y          1    2
##   white   68 4830
##   red   1575   24

1.1.2 Quality of wines

Figure 1.4 shows that it can be hard to figure out significant chemical differences among wines of different quality.

Figure 1.4: Value of features for wines of different quality

However, if we focus on the feature’s median values for wines of different quality as in Figure 1.5, we may expect that at least density and alcohol can distinguish wines of high quality from the rest, and volatile.acidity and free.sulfur.dioxide can differ wines of low quality from others.

Figure 1.5: Median value of features for wines of different quality

After running K-means++ to divide wines into 7 groups (since the actual quality of wines are only ranged from 3 to 9), we do see the some differences in quality emerge naturally from clustering by Figure 1.6.

Figure 1.6: Features by clusters (quality)

However, if we care about the precision of the clustering, the true differences among wines are not accurately captured. Especially, we cannot match the generated clustered with the true groups as we did for color clustering, if we try to compare Figure 1.6 and Figure 1.7. This suggests that the actual quality clusters of points are not convex.

Figure 1.7: Features by actual labels (quality)

The failure of quality clustering can be confirmed again by comparing the actual number of each group and the number of wines in each predicted clusters. If the clusters are capable of classifying the seven levels quality, then the distribution of wine numbers among clusters should look similar to the one among true quality groups. Figure 1.8 shows the distribution are different and thus clustering algorithms cannot precisely distinguish higher from the lower quality wines.

Figure 1.8: Counts of each cluster / quality groups

1.2 Principal component analysis

1.2.1 Color of wines

Next, we consider PCA to see if there are some principal components that can distinguish the reds from the whites, or distinguish wines of different quality. Before that, we would like to take a look at the heatmap (Figure 1.9), which shows that there exist some correlated features that might be able to be summarized by a principal component, like residual.sugar, total.sulfur.dioxide, and free.sulfur.dioxide.

Figure 1.9: Heatmaps of features

The results of PCA show that the first two components can account for about half of the variations.

The preliminary visualization in Figure 1.10 has indicated the significant differences in principal component 1 between red wines and white wines.

Figure 1.10: Value of principal components for wines of different colors

Figure 1.11 further confirmed that we can distinguish the reds from the whites using principal component 1: PC1’s scores tend to higher on the whites than on the reds.

Figure 1.11: Principal components by actual labels (color)

1.2.2 Quality of wines

Figure 1.12 shows that there is no principal components that can significantly differ wines of different quality.

Figure 1.12: Value of principal components for wines of different quality

However, Figure 1.13 shows that principal component 2 and principal component 3 would decrease with quality on average.

Figure 1.13: Median value of principal components for wines of different colors

Figure 1.14 shows that wines of high quality tend to have less principal component 2 and vice versa. But the pattern is not very clear and may not able to classify quality very well.

Figure 1.14: Principal components by actual labels (quality)

2 Q3: Association rules for grocery purchases

In order to obtain the association rules for grocery purchases, here we used the calculation of the Apriori method with the conditions of support=0.005, confidence=0.1 and maxlen=2.

However, it is hard to find the association rules because of so many rules in above plot. Therefore, we would like to use the subset data to make the graph clearly.

We selected the association rules to form a subset with confidence > 0.01, support > 0.005 and 45 rules.

Finally, the graph looks more interesting, reasonable and meaningful. For instance, whipped/sour cream, cream, cheese, and butter point to yogurt, which are possible because they belongs to dairy product. In addition, meat, fruit and vegetables close to other vegetables.
